dward and Park Streets\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1988|12|15}}\n|-\n| [[Village Waterworks]]\n| \n| 337 Lake Shore Road\n| [[Grosse Pointe Farms, Michigan|Grosse Pointe Farms]]\n| {{dts|1995|9|14}}\n|-\n| [[Vinton Building]]\u2020\n| [[File:Vinton Building Detroit MI.jpg|100px]]\n| 600 Woodward Avenue\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1982|11|16}}\n|-\n| [[John Wagner Residence]] (demolished)\n| \n| 468 Peterboro St\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1979|6|15}}\n|-\n| [[Robert Wagstaff House]]\n| [[File:Robert_Wagstaff_House.jpg|100px]]\n| 2576 Riverside Drive\n| [[Trenton, Michigan|Trenton]]\n| {{dts|1986|4|10}}\n|-\n| [[Wallaceville School]]\n| [[File:Wallaceville School historic site Dearborn Heights Michigan.JPG|100px]]\n| 8050 North Gulley Road\n| [[Dearborn Heights, Michigan|Dearborn Heights]]\n| {{dts|1967|2|17}}\n|-\n| [[War of 1812 Dead]] Informational Site\n| \n| Southwest corner of Washington Boulevard and Michigan Avenue\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1962|11|17}}\n|-\n| [[Wardwell House]]\n| [[File:Wardwell House taken from Jefferson Avenue, Grosse Pointe, Michigan.jpg|100px]]\n| 16109 Jefferson Avenue\n| [[Grosse Pointe Park, Michigan|Grosse Pointe Park]]\n| {{dts|1976|8|6}}\n|-\n| [[Wayne County Building|Wayne County Courthouse]]\u2020\n| [[File:Wayne County Bldg Detroit MI USA.JPG|100px]]\n| 600 Randolph Street\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1974|9|17}}\n|-\n| [[Wayne State University]] Informational Designation\n| [[File:Mackenzie House WSU - Detroit Michigan.jpg|100px]]\n| 4735-4841 Cass Avenue\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1957|1|19}}\n|-\n| [[Joseph F. Weber House]]\n| [[File:UsaEast2016 575 Joseph F. Weber House.jpg|100px]]\n| 206 Eliot\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1987|12|17}}\n|-\n| [[Andrew Jackson Welsh House]]\n| \n| 512 West Dunlap\n| [[Northville, Michigan|Northville]]\n| {{dts|1981|2|23}}\n|-\n| [[West Canfield Historic District]]\u2020\n| [[File:West Canfield Historic District 1 - Detroit Michigan.jpg|100px]]\n| West Canfield between Second and Third Avenues\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1970|11|6}}\n|-\n| [[Wheeler Center]]\n| \n| 637 Brewster\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1976|3|2}}\n|-\n| [[David Whitney, Jr. Residence]]\u2020\n| [[File:The Whitney.jpg|100px]]\n| 4421 Woodward Avenue\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1971|12|10}}\n|-\n| [[Wilson Barn]]\u2020\n| [[File:Wilson Barn Livonia MI.jpg|100px]]\n| 9710 Middlebelt Road, NE corner of West Chicago\n| [[Livonia, Michigan|Livonia]]\n| {{dts|1973|11|15}}\n|-\n| [[Detroit Women's City Club|Women's City Club of Detroit]]\u2020\n| [[File:WomansCityClubDetroit.jpg|100px]]\n| 2110 Park Avenue\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1979|4|29}}\n|-\n| [[John Wood Log Cabin]]\n| \n| South side of Middle Gibraltar Road, west of Jefferson\n| [[Gibraltar, Michigan|Gibraltar]]\n| {{dts|1979|8|3}}\n|-\n| [[Brush Park|Woodward East Historic District]]\u2020\n| [[File:Brush Park, Detroit, MI.jpg|100px]]\n| Bounded by Alfred, Edmund, Watson, and Brush and John R streets\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1974|9|17}}\n|-\n| [[Zion Evangelical Lutheran Church (Detroit, Michigan)|Zion Evangelical Lutheran Church]]\n| \n| 4305 Military near Buchanan\n| [[Detroit]]\n| {{dts|1989|2|16}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Wayne County, Michigan]]\n\n==Sources==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120524214709/http://www.mcgi.state.mi.us/hso/advancematch.asp?&cname=&ctype=county&cnty=Wayne&srl=ON Historic Sites Online \u2013 Wayne County]. Michigan State Housing Developmental Authority. Accessed January 4, 2011.\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Michigan State Historic Sites}}\n\n[[Category:Michigan State Historic Sites in Wayne County, Michigan| 01]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Wayne County, Michigan| 01]]\n[[Category:Michigan State Historic Sites by county|Wayne County]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Wayne County, Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Notorious4life", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCurrent listings:image of actual structure (albeit historic)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Michigan_State_Historic_Sites_in_Wayne_County"}
{"title_page": "The Hours (film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = The Hours\n| image = The_Hours_poster.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Stephen Daldry]]\n| producer = [[Scott Rudin]]<br />[[Robert Fox (producer)|Robert Fox]]\n| screenplay = [[David Hare (playwright)|David Hare]]\n| based on = {{Based on|''[[The Hours (novel)|The Hours]]''|[[Michael Cunningham]]}}\n| starring = [[Meryl Streep]]<br />[[Julianne Moore]]<br />[[Nicole Kidman]]<br />[[Ed Harris]]<br />[[Toni Collette]]<br />[[Claire Danes]]<br />[[Jeff Daniels]]<br />[[Stephen Dillane]]<br />[[Allison Janney]]<br />[[John C. Reilly]]<br />[[Miranda Richardson]]\n| music = [[Philip Glass]]\n| cinematography = [[Seamus McGarvey]]\n| editing = [[Peter Boyle (film editor)|Peter Boyle]]\n| studio = Scott Rudin Productions\n| distributor = [[Paramount Pictures]]<br />(North America)<br />[[Miramax Films]]<br />(International)\n| released = {{Film date|2002|12|25|United States|2003|02|14|United Kingdom}}\n| runtime = 114 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 114:38--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/hours-2003-1 | title=''THE HOURS'' (12A) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=January 10, 2003 | accessdate=November 15, 2014}}</ref>\n| country = United States<br />United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| budget = $25 million\n| gross = $108.8 million\n}}\n'''''The Hours''''' is a 2002 [[psychological]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Stephen Daldry]] and starring [[Meryl Streep]], [[Nicole Kidman]], and [[Julianne Moore]]. Supporting roles are played by [[Ed Harris]], [[John C. Reilly]], [[Stephen Dillane]], [[Jeff Daniels]], [[Miranda Richardson]], [[Allison Janney]], [[Toni Collette]], [[Claire Danes]], and [[Eileen Atkins]]. The screenplay by [[David Hare (playwright)|David Hare]] is based on [[Michael Cunningham]]'s 1998 [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning [[The Hours (novel)|novel of the same title]].\n\nThe plot focuses on three women of different generations whose lives are interconnected by the novel ''[[Mrs Dalloway]]'' by [[Virginia Woolf]]. These are Clarissa Vaughan (Streep), a New Yorker preparing an award party for her [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]]-stricken long-time friend and poet, Richard (Harris) in 2001; Laura Brown (Moore), a pregnant 1950s California housewife in an unhappy marriage with a young son; and Virginia Woolf (Kidman) herself in 1920s England, who is struggling with depression and mental illness while trying to write her novel.\n\nThe film was released in Los Angeles and New York City on [[Christmas|Christmas Day]] 2002, and was given a [[limited release]] in the United States and Canada two days later on December 27, 2002. It did not receive a [[wide release]] in North America until January 2003, and was then released in British cinemas on [[Valentine's Day]] that year. Critical reaction to the film was largely positive, with nine [[Academy Award]] nominations for ''The Hours'' including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], and a win for [[Nicole Kidman]] for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]].\n\n==Plot==\nWith the exception of the opening and final scenes, which depict the 1941 [[suicide]] by drowning of [[Virginia Woolf]] in the [[River Ouse, Sussex|River Ouse]], the film takes place within the span of a single day in three different decades and alternates between them throughout the film. The following plot summary has been simplified and is in chronological order, not the order as presented in the film. \n\n=== 1923 ===\nVirginia Woolf has begun writing the book ''[[Mrs Dalloway]]'' in her home in the town of [[Richmond, London|Richmond]] outside [[London]]. Virginia has experienced several [[Mental breakdown|nervous breakdown]]s and suffers from depression. She is constantly under the eye of her servants and her husband, [[Leonard Woolf|Leonard]], who has begun a publishing business at home, [[Hogarth Press]], to stay close to her. Virginia's sister, [[Vanessa Bell|Vanessa]], and her children, [[Julian Bell|Julian]], [[Quentin Bell|Quentin]], and [[Angelica Garnett|Angelica]], come over for an afternoon visit. She and Virginia talk about Vanessa's life in London and Virginia's mental condition. She longs for a life similar to Vanessa, living in London. Vanessa's children find a dead bird. Virginia and Angelica make a funeral for the bird. Virginia lays down just like the bird and looks into the bird\u2019s eyes. She sees herself in the dead bird, suffering and dying in her circumstances. Everyone goes back inside and Virginia continues writing her book. She says that she was going to kill her heroine but instead chooses to kill another character in the book. Before Vanessa leaves, Virginia passionately kisses her sister. It is clear Virginia wants them to stay and wants her sister\u2019s life. After their departure, Virginia flees to the train station, where she is awaiting a train to London. Leonard arrives to bring her home. He tells her how he lives in constant fear that she will take her own life. She says she fears it also but argues that if she is to live, she has the right to decide how and where, stressing that she has the right to decide how her mental condition is treated and wanting to move back to London. Virginia returns home and begins writing again. Leonard questions her as to why someone has to die. Virginia says \u201cIn order that the rest of us should value life more.\u201d Leonard asks who will die and Virginia says \"The poet will die, the visionary.\u201d\n\n=== 1951 ===\nPregnant with her second child, Laura Brown spends her days in her [[Tract housing|tract home]] in Los Angeles with her young son, Richie, and escapes from her conventional life by reading ''Mrs Dalloway''. She married her husband, Dan, soon after [[World War II]]. On the surface they are living the [[American Dream]], but she is nonetheless deeply unhappy. She and Richie make a cake for Dan's birthday, but it is a disaster. Her neighbor Kitty drops in to ask her if she can feed her dog while she's in the hospital for a procedure. Kitty reveals that the procedure is related to the fact that she has been unable to conceive, and may portend permanent infertility, and that she really feels that a woman is not complete until she is a mother. Kitty pretends to be upbeat, but Laura senses her sadness and fear and boldly kisses her on the lips; Kitty acts as if it didn't happen. Laura and Richie successfully make another cake and clean up, and then she takes Richie to stay with a babysitter, Mrs. Latch. Richie runs after his mother as she leaves, fearing that she will never come back. Laura checks into a hotel, where she intends to commit suicide. Laura removes several bottles of pills and ''Mrs Dalloway'' from her purse and begins to read it. She drifts off to sleep and dreams the hotel room is flooded. She awakens with a change of heart and caresses her belly. She picks up Richie, who fearfully tells his mother he loves her, and they return home to celebrate Dan's birthday.\n\n=== 2001 ===\nNew Yorker Clarissa Vaughan is the embodiment of the novel's title character. She spends the day preparing for a party she is hosting in honor of her former lover and friend Richard, a poet and author living with [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] who is to receive a major literary award. Clarissa, who is bisexual and has been living with Sally Lester for 10 years, was in a relationship with Richard during their college years. She meets with Richard's ex-lover Louis Waters, who has returned for the festivities. Clarissa's daughter, Julia, comes home to help her prepare. Clarissa visits Richard and he tells Clarissa that he has stayed alive for her sake and that the award is meaningless because he didn't get it sooner, until he was on the brink of death. She tries reassuring him. Richard often refers to Clarissa as \"Mrs. Dalloway\" \u2013 her namesake \u2013 because she distracts herself from her own life the way that the Woolf character does. Richard tells Clarissa that she is the most beautiful thing that he ever had in life, before he commits suicide in front of her. Later that night, Richard's mother, Laura Brown, arrives at Clarissa's apartment. Laura is aware that her abandonment of her family was deeply traumatic for Richard, but Laura reveals that it was a better decision for her to leave the family after the birth of her daughter than to commit suicide. She does not apologize for the hurt that she caused to her family and suggests that it's not possible to feel regret for something over which she had no choice. She acknowledges that no one will forgive her, but she offers an explanation: \"It was death. I chose life.\"\n\nThe film ends with Virginia's suicide by drowning with a voice-over in which Virginia thanks Leonard for loving her: \"Always the years between us. Always the years. Always the love. Always the hours.\"\n\n==Cast==\n;1923\n* [[Nicole Kidman]] as [[Virginia Woolf]]\n* [[Stephen Dillane]] as [[Leonard Woolf]]\n* [[Miranda Richardson]] as [[Vanessa Bell]]\n* [[Lyndsey Marshal]] as Lottie Hope\n* [[Linda Bassett]] as Nelly Boxall\n*George Loftus as [[Quentin Bell]]\n*Charley Ramm as [[Julian Bell]]\n*Sophie Wyburd as [[Angelica Garnett|Angelica Bell]]\n\n;1951\n* [[Julianne Moore]] as Laura Brown\n* [[John C. Reilly]] as Dan Brown\n* [[Jack Rovello]] as Richard \"Richie\" Brown\n* [[Toni Collette]] as Kitty\n* [[Margo Martindale]] as Mrs. Latch\n\n;2001\n* [[Meryl Streep]] as Clarissa Vaughan\n* [[Ed Harris]] as Richard \"Richie\" Brown\n* [[Allison Janney]] as Sally Lester\n* [[Claire Danes]] as Julia Vaughan\n* [[Jeff Daniels]] as Louis Waters\n* [[Eileen Atkins]] as Barbara\n* [[Julianne Moore]] as Older Laura Brown\n\n==Critical reception==\nCritics praised Daldry's direction, the musical score, and the performances of the three central characters. Kidman's performance was widely acclaimed, and she won numerous awards for her portrayal of Virginia Woolf, including the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]]. ''The Hours'' has an 80% \"fresh\" rating on the film review aggregator site [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 193 reviews and an average rating of 7.4/10. The consensus says that \"the movie may be a downer, but it packs an emotional wallop. Some fine acting on display here.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/hours/|title=''The Hours''|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds an average score of 80 out of 100, based on 40 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/video/titles/hours|title=''The Hours''|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Richard Schickel]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' criticized the film's simplistic characterization, saying, \"Watching ''The Hours'', one finds oneself focusing excessively on the unfortunate prosthetic nose Kidman affects in order to look more like the novelist. And wondering why the screenwriter, David Hare, and the director, Stephen Daldry, turn Woolf, a woman of incisive mind, into a hapless ditherer.\" He also criticized its overt politicization: \"But this movie is in love with female victimization. Moore's Laura is trapped in the suburban flatlands of the '50s, while Streep's Clarissa is moored in a hopeless love for Laura's homosexual son (Ed Harris, in a truly ugly performance), an AIDS sufferer whose relentless anger is directly traceable to Mom's long-ago desertion of him. Somehow, despite the complexity of the film's structure, this all seems too simple-minded. Or should we perhaps say agenda driven? This ultimately proves insufficient to lend meaning to their lives or profundity to a grim and uninvolving film, for which Philip Glass unwittingly provides the perfect score \u2014 tuneless, oppressive, droning, painfully self-important.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1003931,00.html|title=Holiday Movie Preview: The Hours|author=RICHARD SCHICKEL|date=December 23, 2002|accessdate=July 19, 2010|publisher=Time.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Stephen Holden]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called the film \"deeply moving\" and \"an amazingly faithful screen adaptation\" and added, \"Although suicide eventually tempts three of the film's characters, ''The Hours'' is not an unduly morbid film. Clear eyed and austerely balanced would be a more accurate description, along with magnificently written and acted. Mr. Glass's surging minimalist score, with its air of cosmic abstraction, serves as ideal connective tissue for a film that breaks down temporal barriers.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Holden |first=Stephen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/27/movies/27HOUR.html |title=Who's Afraid Like Virginia Woolf? |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 27, 2002 |accessdate=July 19, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204232423/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/27/movies/27HOUR.html |archivedate=December 4, 2009}}</ref> [[Mick LaSalle]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' observed, \"Director Stephen Daldry employs the wonderful things cinema can do in order to realize aspects of ''The Hours'' that Cunningham could only hint at or approximate on the page. The result is something rare, especially considering how fine the novel is, a film that's fuller and deeper than the book ... It's marvelous to watch the ways in which [David Hare] consistently dramatizes the original material without compromising its integrity or distorting its intent ... Cunningham's [novel] touched on notes of longing, middle-aged angst and the sense of being a small consciousness in the midst of a grand mystery. But Daldry and Hare's [film] sounds those notes and sends audiences out reverberating with them, exalted.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Mick |last=LaSalle |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2002/12/27/DD114138.DTL |title=Film proves to be book's finest 'Hours' / Kidman, Moore, Streep lift story even higher |publisher=Sfgate.com |date=December 27, 2002 |accessdate=July 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' awarded the film, which he thought \"sometimes stumbles on literary pretensions,\" three out of four stars. He praised the performances, commenting, \"Kidman's acting is superlative, full of passion and feeling ... Moore is wrenching in her scenes with Laura's son (Jack Rovello, an exceptional child actor). And Streep is a miracle worker, building a character in the space between words and worlds. These three unimprovable actresses make ''The Hours'' a thing of beauty.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/the-hours-20030124 |title=The Hours |last=Traver |first=Peter |date=January 24, 2003 |access-date=September 25, 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Philip French]] of ''[[The Observer]]'' called it \"a moving, somewhat depressing film that demands and rewards attention.\" He thought \"the performances are remarkable\" but found the Philip Glass score to be \"relentless\" and \"over-amplified.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Phillip French |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2003/feb/16/7 |title=Take three women |publisher=Guardian |date= February 16, 2003|accessdate=July 19, 2010 | location=London}}</ref> Steve Persall of the ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'' said it \"is the most finely crafted film of the past year that I never want to sit through again. The performances are flawless, the screenplay is intelligently crafted, and the overall mood is relentlessly bleak. It is a film to be admired, not embraced, and certainly not to be enjoyed for any reason other than its expertise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2003/01/16/Weekend/_The_Hours__drags_on_.shtml |title='&#39;St. Petersburg Times'&#39; review |publisher=Sptimes.com |date= |accessdate=July 19, 2010}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' rated the film three out of five stars and commented, \"It is a daring act of extrapolation, and a real departure from most movie-making, which can handle only one universe at a time . . . The performances that Daldry elicits . . . are all strong: tightly managed, smoothly and dashingly juxtaposed under a plangent score . . . Part of the bracing experimental impact of the film was the absence of narrative connection between the three women. Supplying one in the final reel undermines its formal daring, but certainly packs an emotional punch. It makes for an elegant and poignant chamber music of the soul.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Peter Bradshaw |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2003/feb/14/artsfeatures |title='&#39;The Guardian'&#39; review |publisher=Guardian |date=February 14, 2003 |accessdate=July 19, 2010 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Box office==\n''The Hours'' opened in [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]] on [[Christmas|Christmas Day]] 2002 and went into limited release in the United States and Canada two days later. It grossed $1,070,856 on eleven screens in its first two weeks of release. On January 10, 2003, it expanded to 45 screens, and the following week it expanded to 402. On February 14 it went into wide release, playing in 1,003 theaters in the US and Canada.<ref name=bom>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=hours.htm |title=The Hours|work=Box Office Mojo|date=December 27, 2002|accessdate=July 19, 2010}}</ref> With an estimated budget of $25 million, the film eventually earned $41,675,994 in the US and Canada and $67,170,078 in foreign markets for a total worldwide box office of $108,846,072. It was the 47th highest-grossing film of 2002.<ref name=bom/>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|The Hours (soundtrack)}}\nThe film's score by [[Philip Glass]] won the [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Music]] and was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Score]] and the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score]]. The [[The Hours (soundtrack)|soundtrack album]] was nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack Album for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]].\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of accolades received by The Hours}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Taylor, C. J. (2015). ''The Hours'' - A film to enhance teaching psychology. ''Academic Exchange Quarterly'', 19(2), 17\u201322.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|The Hours (film)|The Hours}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.miramax.com/movie/the-hours}}\n* {{IMDb title|0274558|The Hours}}\n* {{mojo title|hours|The Hours}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|hours|The Hours}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-hours|The Hours}}\n* ''[http://www.vintagecarriagestrust.org/news/2001aug.pdf The Hours]''[http://www.vintagecarriagestrust.org/news/2001aug.pdf  - filming the railway sequences]\n\n{{Virginia Woolf}}\n{{David Hare}}\n{{Stephen Daldry}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by The Hours|Awards for ''The Hours'']]\n|list =\n{{GLAAD Media Award for Outstanding Film \u2013 Wide Release}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestMotionPictureDrama 2001-2020}}\n{{Guldbagge Award Best Foreign Film}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Film}}\n{{Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hours}}\n[[Category:2002 films]]\n[[Category:2002 drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British drama films]]\n[[Category:British LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Stephen Daldry]]\n[[Category:Films about gender]]\n[[Category:Best Drama Picture Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Philip Glass]]\n[[Category:2000s feminist films]]\n[[Category:Films about bipolar disorder]]\n[[Category:Films about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Films about suicide]]\n[[Category:Films about writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Drama Actress Golden Globe-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Best Foreign Film Guldbagge Award winners]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Films set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1923]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1941]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1951]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2001]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in film]]\n[[Category:American nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:Virginia Woolf in performing arts]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Virginia Woolf]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Pinewood Studios]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Scott Rudin]]\n[[Category:Films about depression]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about writers]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = The Hours\n| image = The_Hours_poster.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Stephen Daldry]]\n| producer = [[Scott Rudin]]<br />[[Robert Fox (producer)|Robert Fox]]\n| screenplay = [[David Hare (playwright)|David Hare]]\n| based on = {{Based on|''[[The Hours (novel)|The Hours]]''|[[Michael Cunningham]]}}\n| starring = [[Meryl Streep]]<br />[[Julianne Moore]]<br />[[Nicole Kidman]]<br />[[Ed Harris]]<br />[[Toni Collette]]<br />[[Claire Danes]]<br />[[Jeff Daniels]]<br />[[Stephen Dillane]]<br />[[Allison Janney]]<br />[[John C. Reilly]]<br />[[Miranda Richardson]]\n| music = [[Philip Glass]]\n| cinematography = [[Seamus McGarvey]]\n| editing = [[Peter Boyle (film editor)|Peter Boyle]]\n| studio = Scott Rudin Productions\n| distributor = [[Paramount Pictures]]<br />(North America)<br />[[Miramax Films]]<br />(International)\n| released = {{Film date|2002|12|25|United States|2003|02|14|United Kingdom}}\n| runtime = 114 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 114:38--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/hours-2003-1 | title=''THE HOURS'' (12A) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=January 10, 2003 | accessdate=November 15, 2014}}</ref>\n| country = United States<br />United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| budget = $25 million\n| gross = $108.8 million\n}}\n'''''The Hours''''' is a 2002 [[psychological]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Stephen Daldry]] and starring [[Meryl Streep]], [[Nicole Kidman]], and [[Julianne Moore]]. Supporting roles are played by [[Ed Harris]], [[John C. Reilly]], [[Stephen Dillane]], [[Jeff Daniels]], [[Miranda Richardson]], [[Allison Janney]], [[Toni Collette]], [[Claire Danes]], and [[Eileen Atkins]]. The screenplay by [[David Hare (playwright)|David Hare]] is based on [[Michael Cunningham]]'s 1998 [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning [[The Hours (novel)|novel of the same title]].\n\nThe plot focuses on three women of different generations whose lives are interconnected by the novel ''[[Mrs Dalloway]]'' by [[Virginia Woolf]]. These are Clarissa Vaughan (Streep), a New Yorker preparing an award party for her [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]]-stricken long-time friend and poet, Richard (Harris) in 2001; Laura Brown (Moore), a pregnant 1950s California housewife in an unhappy marriage with a young son; and Virginia Woolf (Kidman) herself in 1920s England, who is struggling with depression and mental illness while trying to write her novel.\n\nThe film was released in Los Angeles and New York City on [[Christmas|Christmas Day]] 2002, and was given a [[limited release]] in the United States and Canada two days later on December 27, 2002. It did not receive a [[wide release]] in North America until January 2003, and was then released in British cinemas on [[Valentine's Day]] that year. Critical reaction to the film was largely positive, with nine [[Academy Award]] nominations for ''The Hours'' including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], and a win for [[Nicole Kidman]] for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]].\n\n==Plot==\nWith the exception of the opening and final scenes, which depict the 1941 [[suicide]] by drowning of [[Virginia Woolf]] in the [[River Ouse, Sussex|River Ouse]], the film takes place within the span of a single day in three different decades and alternates between them throughout the film. The following plot summary has been simplified and is in chronological order, not the order as presented in the film. \n\n=== 1923 ===\nVirginia Woolf has begun writing the book ''[[Mrs Dalloway]]'' in her home in the town of [[Richmond, London|Richmond]] outside [[London]]. Virginia has experienced several [[Mental breakdown|nervous breakdown]]s and suffers from depression. She is constantly under the eye of her servants and her husband, [[Leonard Woolf|Leonard]], who has begun a publishing business at home, [[Hogarth Press]], to stay close to her. Virginia's sister, [[Vanessa Bell|Vanessa]], and her children, [[Julian Bell|Julian]], [[Quentin Bell|Quentin]], and [[Angelica Garnett|Angelica]], come over for an afternoon visit. She and Virginia talk about Vanessa's life in London and Virginia's mental condition. She longs for a life similar to Vanessa, living in London. Vanessa's children find a dead bird. Virginia and Angelica make a funeral for the bird. Virginia lays down just like the bird and looks into the bird\u2019s eyes. She sees herself in the dead bird, suffering and dying in her circumstances. Everyone goes back inside and Virginia continues writing her book. She says that she was going to kill her heroine but instead chooses to kill another character in the book. Before Vanessa leaves, Virginia passionately kisses her sister. It is clear Virginia wants them to stay and wants her sister\u2019s life. After their departure, Virginia flees to the train station, where she is awaiting a train to London. Leonard arrives to bring her home. He tells her how he lives in constant fear that she will take her own life. She says she fears it also but argues that if she is to live, she has the right to decide how and where, stressing that she has the right to decide how her mental condition is treated and wanting to move back to London. Virginia returns home and begins writing again. Leonard questions her as to why someone has to die. Virginia says \u201cin order that the rest of us should value life more.\u201d Leonard asks who will die and Virginia says the \u201cpoet, the visionary.\u201d\n\n=== 1951 ===\nPregnant with her second child, Laura Brown spends her days in her [[Tract housing|tract home]] in Los Angeles with her young son, Richie, and escapes from her conventional life by reading ''Mrs Dalloway''. She married her husband, Dan, soon after [[World War II]]. On the surface they are living the [[American Dream]], but she is nonetheless deeply unhappy. She and Richie make a cake for Dan's birthday, but it is a disaster. Her neighbor Kitty drops in to ask her if she can feed her dog while she's in the hospital for a procedure. Kitty reveals that the procedure is related to the fact that she has been unable to conceive, and may portend permanent infertility, and that she really feels that a woman is not complete until she is a mother. Kitty pretends to be upbeat, but Laura senses her sadness and fear and boldly kisses her on the lips; Kitty acts as if it didn't happen. Laura and Richie successfully make another cake and clean up, and then she takes Richie to stay with a babysitter, Mrs. Latch. Richie runs after his mother as she leaves, fearing that she will never come back. Laura checks into a hotel, where she intends to commit suicide. Laura removes several bottles of pills and ''Mrs Dalloway'' from her purse and begins to read it. She drifts off to sleep and dreams the hotel room is flooded. She awakens with a change of heart and caresses her belly. She picks up Richie, who fearfully tells his mother he loves her, and they return home to celebrate Dan's birthday.\n\n=== 2001 ===\nNew Yorker Clarissa Vaughan is the embodiment of the novel's title character. She spends the day preparing for a party she is hosting in honor of her former lover and friend Richard, a poet and author living with [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] who is to receive a major literary award. Clarissa, who is bisexual and has been living with Sally Lester for 10 years, was in a relationship with Richard during their college years. She meets with Richard's ex-lover Louis Waters, who has returned for the festivities. Clarissa's daughter, Julia, comes home to help her prepare. Clarissa visits Richard and he tells Clarissa that he has stayed alive for her sake and that the award is meaningless because he didn't get it sooner, until he was on the brink of death. She tries reassuring him. Richard often refers to Clarissa as \"Mrs. Dalloway\" \u2013 her namesake \u2013 because she distracts herself from her own life the way that the Woolf character does. Richard tells Clarissa that she is the most beautiful thing that he ever had in life, before he commits suicide in front of her. Later that night, Richard's mother, Laura Brown, arrives at Clarissa's apartment. Laura is aware that her abandonment of her family was deeply traumatic for Richard, but Laura reveals that it was a better decision for her to leave the family after the birth of her daughter than to commit suicide. She does not apologize for the hurt that she caused to her family and suggests that it's not possible to feel regret for something over which she had no choice. She acknowledges that no one will forgive her, but she offers an explanation: \"It was death. I chose life.\"\n\nThe film ends with Virginia's suicide by drowning with a voice-over in which Virginia thanks Leonard for loving her: \"Always the years between us. Always the years. Always the love. Always the hours.\"\n\n==Cast==\n;1923\n* [[Nicole Kidman]] as [[Virginia Woolf]]\n* [[Stephen Dillane]] as [[Leonard Woolf]]\n* [[Miranda Richardson]] as [[Vanessa Bell]]\n* [[Lyndsey Marshal]] as Lottie Hope\n* [[Linda Bassett]] as Nelly Boxall\n*George Loftus as [[Quentin Bell]]\n*Charley Ramm as [[Julian Bell]]\n*Sophie Wyburd as [[Angelica Garnett|Angelica Bell]]\n\n;1951\n* [[Julianne Moore]] as Laura Brown\n* [[John C. Reilly]] as Dan Brown\n* [[Jack Rovello]] as Richard \"Richie\" Brown\n* [[Toni Collette]] as Kitty\n* [[Margo Martindale]] as Mrs. Latch\n\n;2001\n* [[Meryl Streep]] as Clarissa Vaughan\n* [[Ed Harris]] as Richard \"Richie\" Brown\n* [[Allison Janney]] as Sally Lester\n* [[Claire Danes]] as Julia Vaughan\n* [[Jeff Daniels]] as Louis Waters\n* [[Eileen Atkins]] as Barbara\n* [[Julianne Moore]] as Older Laura Brown\n\n==Critical reception==\nCritics praised Daldry's direction, the musical score, and the performances of the three central characters. Kidman's performance was widely acclaimed, and she won numerous awards for her portrayal of Virginia Woolf, including the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]]. ''The Hours'' has an 80% \"fresh\" rating on the film review aggregator site [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 193 reviews and an average rating of 7.4/10. The consensus says that \"the movie may be a downer, but it packs an emotional wallop. Some fine acting on display here.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/hours/|title=''The Hours''|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds an average score of 80 out of 100, based on 40 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/video/titles/hours|title=''The Hours''|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Richard Schickel]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' criticized the film's simplistic characterization, saying, \"Watching ''The Hours'', one finds oneself focusing excessively on the unfortunate prosthetic nose Kidman affects in order to look more like the novelist. And wondering why the screenwriter, David Hare, and the director, Stephen Daldry, turn Woolf, a woman of incisive mind, into a hapless ditherer.\" He also criticized its overt politicization: \"But this movie is in love with female victimization. Moore's Laura is trapped in the suburban flatlands of the '50s, while Streep's Clarissa is moored in a hopeless love for Laura's homosexual son (Ed Harris, in a truly ugly performance), an AIDS sufferer whose relentless anger is directly traceable to Mom's long-ago desertion of him. Somehow, despite the complexity of the film's structure, this all seems too simple-minded. Or should we perhaps say agenda driven? This ultimately proves insufficient to lend meaning to their lives or profundity to a grim and uninvolving film, for which Philip Glass unwittingly provides the perfect score \u2014 tuneless, oppressive, droning, painfully self-important.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1003931,00.html|title=Holiday Movie Preview: The Hours|author=RICHARD SCHICKEL|date=December 23, 2002|accessdate=July 19, 2010|publisher=Time.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Stephen Holden]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called the film \"deeply moving\" and \"an amazingly faithful screen adaptation\" and added, \"Although suicide eventually tempts three of the film's characters, ''The Hours'' is not an unduly morbid film. Clear eyed and austerely balanced would be a more accurate description, along with magnificently written and acted. Mr. Glass's surging minimalist score, with its air of cosmic abstraction, serves as ideal connective tissue for a film that breaks down temporal barriers.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Holden |first=Stephen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/27/movies/27HOUR.html |title=Who's Afraid Like Virginia Woolf? |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 27, 2002 |accessdate=July 19, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204232423/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/27/movies/27HOUR.html |archivedate=December 4, 2009}}</ref> [[Mick LaSalle]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' observed, \"Director Stephen Daldry employs the wonderful things cinema can do in order to realize aspects of ''The Hours'' that Cunningham could only hint at or approximate on the page. The result is something rare, especially considering how fine the novel is, a film that's fuller and deeper than the book ... It's marvelous to watch the ways in which [David Hare] consistently dramatizes the original material without compromising its integrity or distorting its intent ... Cunningham's [novel] touched on notes of longing, middle-aged angst and the sense of being a small consciousness in the midst of a grand mystery. But Daldry and Hare's [film] sounds those notes and sends audiences out reverberating with them, exalted.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Mick |last=LaSalle |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2002/12/27/DD114138.DTL |title=Film proves to be book's finest 'Hours' / Kidman, Moore, Streep lift story even higher |publisher=Sfgate.com |date=December 27, 2002 |accessdate=July 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' awarded the film, which he thought \"sometimes stumbles on literary pretensions,\" three out of four stars. He praised the performances, commenting, \"Kidman's acting is superlative, full of passion and feeling ... Moore is wrenching in her scenes with Laura's son (Jack Rovello, an exceptional child actor). And Streep is a miracle worker, building a character in the space between words and worlds. These three unimprovable actresses make ''The Hours'' a thing of beauty.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/the-hours-20030124 |title=The Hours |last=Traver |first=Peter |date=January 24, 2003 |access-date=September 25, 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Philip French]] of ''[[The Observer]]'' called it \"a moving, somewhat depressing film that demands and rewards attention.\" He thought \"the performances are remarkable\" but found the Philip Glass score to be \"relentless\" and \"over-amplified.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Phillip French |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2003/feb/16/7 |title=Take three women |publisher=Guardian |date= February 16, 2003|accessdate=July 19, 2010 | location=London}}</ref> Steve Persall of the ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'' said it \"is the most finely crafted film of the past year that I never want to sit through again. The performances are flawless, the screenplay is intelligently crafted, and the overall mood is relentlessly bleak. It is a film to be admired, not embraced, and certainly not to be enjoyed for any reason other than its expertise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2003/01/16/Weekend/_The_Hours__drags_on_.shtml |title='&#39;St. Petersburg Times'&#39; review |publisher=Sptimes.com |date= |accessdate=July 19, 2010}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' rated the film three out of five stars and commented, \"It is a daring act of extrapolation, and a real departure from most movie-making, which can handle only one universe at a time . . . The performances that Daldry elicits . . . are all strong: tightly managed, smoothly and dashingly juxtaposed under a plangent score . . . Part of the bracing experimental impact of the film was the absence of narrative connection between the three women. Supplying one in the final reel undermines its formal daring, but certainly packs an emotional punch. It makes for an elegant and poignant chamber music of the soul.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Peter Bradshaw |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2003/feb/14/artsfeatures |title='&#39;The Guardian'&#39; review |publisher=Guardian |date=February 14, 2003 |accessdate=July 19, 2010 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Box office==\n''The Hours'' opened in [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]] on [[Christmas|Christmas Day]] 2002 and went into limited release in the United States and Canada two days later. It grossed $1,070,856 on eleven screens in its first two weeks of release. On January 10, 2003, it expanded to 45 screens, and the following week it expanded to 402. On February 14 it went into wide release, playing in 1,003 theaters in the US and Canada.<ref name=bom>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=hours.htm |title=The Hours|work=Box Office Mojo|date=December 27, 2002|accessdate=July 19, 2010}}</ref> With an estimated budget of $25 million, the film eventually earned $41,675,994 in the US and Canada and $67,170,078 in foreign markets for a total worldwide box office of $108,846,072. It was the 47th highest-grossing film of 2002.<ref name=bom/>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|The Hours (soundtrack)}}\nThe film's score by [[Philip Glass]] won the [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Music]] and was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Score]] and the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score]]. The [[The Hours (soundtrack)|soundtrack album]] was nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack Album for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]].\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of accolades received by The Hours}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Taylor, C. J. (2015). ''The Hours'' - A film to enhance teaching psychology. ''Academic Exchange Quarterly'', 19(2), 17\u201322.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|The Hours (film)|The Hours}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.miramax.com/movie/the-hours}}\n* {{IMDb title|0274558|The Hours}}\n* {{mojo title|hours|The Hours}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|hours|The Hours}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-hours|The Hours}}\n* ''[http://www.vintagecarriagestrust.org/news/2001aug.pdf The Hours]''[http://www.vintagecarriagestrust.org/news/2001aug.pdf  - filming the railway sequences]\n\n{{Virginia Woolf}}\n{{David Hare}}\n{{Stephen Daldry}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by The Hours|Awards for ''The Hours'']]\n|list =\n{{GLAAD Media Award for Outstanding Film \u2013 Wide Release}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestMotionPictureDrama 2001-2020}}\n{{Guldbagge Award Best Foreign Film}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Film}}\n{{Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hours}}\n[[Category:2002 films]]\n[[Category:2002 drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British drama films]]\n[[Category:British LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Stephen Daldry]]\n[[Category:Films about gender]]\n[[Category:Best Drama Picture Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Philip Glass]]\n[[Category:2000s feminist films]]\n[[Category:Films about bipolar disorder]]\n[[Category:Films about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Films about suicide]]\n[[Category:Films about writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Drama Actress Golden Globe-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Best Foreign Film Guldbagge Award winners]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Films set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1923]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1941]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1951]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2001]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in film]]\n[[Category:American nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:Virginia Woolf in performing arts]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Virginia Woolf]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Pinewood Studios]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Scott Rudin]]\n[[Category:Films about depression]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about writers]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n", "name_user": "Factfanatic1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1923", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hours_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Shy heathwren", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Shy heathwren\n| image = Hylacola cauta Wilpena Pound.JPG\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucnredlist\">{{cite iucn |title=Calamanthus cautus (Shy Heathwren, Shy Hylacola) |url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704614/0 |accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n| genus = Hylacola\n| species = cauta\n| authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1843\n| synonyms = ''Calamanthus cautus''<br>''Hylacola cautus''<br>''Sericornis cautus''\n}}\n\nThe '''shy heathwren''' (''Hylacola cauta'') is a species of small [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]], [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Australia]]. They inhabit mostly [[Mallee (habit)|mallee]] woodland that has relatively dense shrub and [[Heath (habitat)|heath]] understorey. Shy heathwrens feed mostly on ground dwelling insects; rarely on seeds. Their ground level nests are dome-shaped and usually concealed within grass [[Bunch grass|tussocks]] or shrubs.<ref name=\"NSWsite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.threatenedspecies.environment.nsw.gov.au/tsprofile/profile.aspx?id=10125|title=Shy Heathwren \u2013 Profile|publisher=Department of Environment and Climate Change, NSW|accessdate=2008-06-05}}</ref> Within the nest they typically lay 2\u20133 freckled and pinkish eggs.<ref name=\"Slater\">{{cite book|last=Slater|first=Peter|author2=Slater, Pat |author3=Slater, Raoul |title=[[The Slater Field Guide to Australian Birds]]|publisher=Landsdowne|location=Sydney|year=1993|edition=Revised|pages=258|isbn=0-947116-99-0}}</ref>\n\nThe birds are cock-tailed with a chestnut rump that darkens towards the tip. Their feathers are white with brown streaking underneath and greyish-brown on the back and crown. They have a white eyebrow, tail tip and patch on the [[flight feather]]s, and a black [[Beak|bill]]. Their eyes are brown to yellowish-brown and legs are slate-brown. Females have slightly duller colouring, and immature birds duller again with some of these being fawn-coloured underneath.<ref name=\"Slater\" /><ref name=\"NSWsite\" /> They have a total length when adults from 11 to 14 centimetres.<ref>listed as 12\u201314 cm in Slater P.(1993) but 11\u201314 cm by the Department of Environment and Climate Change, NSW</ref>\n\nThey are uncommon residents across a wide part of southern Australia. Ranging from near [[West Wyalong, New South Wales|West Wyalong]] in [[New South Wales]] to the [[Murchison River (Western Australia)|Murchison River]] in [[Western Australia]].<ref name=\"Slater\" /> In New South Wales, they are found in two isolated populations: one between [[Leeton, New South Wales|Leeton]], Willandra, [[New South Wales]], [[Nymagee, New South Wales|Nymagee]] and West Wyalong; and the other from [[Balranald, New South Wales|Balranald]] to [[Trentham Cliffs, New South Wales|Trentham Cliffs]]. Within the state they are seen as a [[threatened]] and [[vulnerable]] species, largely due to human-wrought [[Habitat destruction|habitat loss]], and [[predation]] by foxes and cats.<ref name=\"NSWsite\" />\n\nTheir [[Alpha taxonomy|taxonomic]] name was formerly ''Calamanthus cautus''\u2014classing them as fieldwrens\u2014until they were renamed in 2008.<ref>{{cite book|last=Christidis|first=L|author2=Boles, W.E |title=Systematics and Taxonomy of Australian Birds|publisher=CSIRO Publishing|location=Collingwood, Victoria|year=2008|isbn=978-0-643-06511-6}}</ref> The generic name ''Hylacola'' derives from the Greek ''hyl\u0113'' 'woodland' and the latin ''-cola'' 'dweller'.<ref name=Helm>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-18}}</ref> The specific epithet derives from the Latin ''cautus'' 'shy, wary'.<ref name=Helm></ref> Common names for the species include shy hylacola<ref name=\"iucnredlist\" /> and mallee heathwren<ref>Pizzey, Graham; Doyle, Roy (1980) A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia. Collins Publishers, Sydney. ISBN 073222436-5</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075267}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:heathwren, shy}}\n[[Category:Hylacola|shy heathwren]]\n[[Category:Birds of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1843|shy heathwren]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Shy heathwren\n| image = Hylacola cauta Wilpena Pound.JPG\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucnredlist\">{{cite iucn |title=Calamanthus cautus (Shy Heathwren, Shy Hylacola) |url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704614/0 |accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n| genus = Hylacola\n| species = cauta\n| authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1843\n| synonyms = ''Calamanthus cautus''<br>''Hylacola cautus''<br>''Sericornis cautus''\n}}\n\nThe '''shy heathwren''' (''Hylacola cauta'') is a species of small [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]], [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Australia]]. They inhabit mostly [[Mallee (habit)|mallee]] woodland that has relatively dense shrub and [[Heath (habitat)|heath]] understorey. Shy heathwrens feed mostly on ground dwelling insects; rarely on seeds. Their ground level nests are dome-shaped and usually concealed within grass [[Bunch grass|tussocks]] or shrubs.<ref name=\"NSWsite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.threatenedspecies.environment.nsw.gov.au/tsprofile/profile.aspx?id=10125|title=Shy Heathwren \u2013 Profile|publisher=Department of Environment and Climate Change, NSW|accessdate=2008-06-05}}</ref> Within the nest they typically lay 2\u20133 freckled and pinkish eggs.<ref name=\"Slater\">{{cite book|last=Slater|first=Peter|author2=Slater, Pat |author3=Slater, Raoul |title=[[The Slater Field Guide to Australian Birds]]|publisher=Landsdowne|location=Sydney|year=1993|edition=Revised|pages=258|isbn=0-947116-99-0}}</ref>\n\nThe birds are cock-tailed with a chestnut rump that darkens towards the tip. Their feathers are white with brown streaking underneath and greyish-brown on the back and crown. They have a white eyebrow, tail tip and patch on the [[flight feather]]s, and a black [[Beak|bill]]. Their eyes are brown to yellowish-brown and legs are slate-brown. Females have slightly duller colouring, and immature birds duller again with some of these being fawn-coloured underneath.<ref name=\"Slater\" /><ref name=\"NSWsite\" /> They have a total length when adults from 11 to 14 centimetres.<ref>listed as 12\u201314 in Slater P.(1993) but 11\u201314 by the Department of Environment and Climate Change, NSW</ref>\n\nThey are uncommon residents across a wide part of southern Australia. Ranging from near [[West Wyalong, New South Wales|West Wyalong]] in [[New South Wales]] to the [[Murchison River (Western Australia)|Murchison River]] in [[Western Australia]].<ref name=\"Slater\" /> In New South Wales, they are found in two isolated populations: one between [[Leeton, New South Wales|Leeton]], Willandra, [[New South Wales]], [[Nymagee, New South Wales|Nymagee]] and West Wyalong; and the other from [[Balranald, New South Wales|Balranald]] to [[Trentham Cliffs, New South Wales|Trentham Cliffs]]. Within the state they are seen as a [[threatened]] and [[vulnerable]] species, largely due to human-wrought [[Habitat destruction|habitat loss]], and [[predation]] by foxes and cats.<ref name=\"NSWsite\" />\n\nTheir [[Alpha taxonomy|taxonomic]] name was formerly ''Calamanthus cautus''\u2014classing them as fieldwrens\u2014until they were renamed in 2008.<ref>{{cite book|last=Christidis|first=L|author2=Boles, W.E |title=Systematics and Taxonomy of Australian Birds|publisher=CSIRO Publishing|location=Collingwood, Victoria|year=2008|isbn=978-0-643-06511-6}}</ref> The generic name ''Hylacola'' derives from the Greek ''hyl\u0113'' 'woodland' and the latin ''-cola'' 'dweller'.<ref name=Helm>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-18}}</ref> The specific epithet derives from the Latin ''cautus'' 'shy, wary'.<ref name=Helm></ref> Common names for the species include shy hylacola<ref name=\"iucnredlist\" /> and mallee heathwren<ref>Pizzey, Graham; Doyle, Roy (1980) A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia. Collins Publishers, Sydney. ISBN 073222436-5</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075267}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:heathwren, shy}}\n[[Category:Hylacola|shy heathwren]]\n[[Category:Birds of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1843|shy heathwren]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shy_heathwren"}
{"title_page": "Mercabarna (Barcelona Metro)", "text_new": "{{Infobox station\n| name            = Mercabarna\n| type            = [[Barcelona Metro]] [[rapid transit]] station\n| style           = \n| image           = File:Estaci\u00f3 de Mercabarna.jpg\n| image_caption   = \n| address         = Mercabarna, [[Barcelona]]\n| country         = \n| coordinates     = {{coord|41|20|01|N|2|01|42|E|region:ES-CT_type:landmark_source:kolossus-nlwiki|display=inline,title}}\n| line            = \n| other           = \n| structure       = Underground\n| platform        = \n| depth           = \n| levels          = \n| tracks          = \n| parking         = \n| bicycle         = \n| opened          = 2016\n| closed          = \n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = \n| ADA             = \n| code            = \n| owned           = [[Transports Metropolitans de Barcelona]]\n| zone            = 1 ([[Autoritat del Transport Metropolit\u00e0|ATM]])\n| smartcardname   = \n| smartcardstatus = \n| former          = \n| passengers      = \n| pass_year       = \n| pass_percent    = \n| pass_system     = \n| mpassengers     = \n| services        = {{S-rail|title=Barcelona Metro}}\n{{S-line|system=Barcelona Metro|line=L9S|previous=Les Moreres|next=Parc Log\u00edstic}}\n| map_type        = Spain Province of Barcelona#Spain\n| map_caption     = Location in Province##Location in Spain\n}}\n\n'''Mercabarna''' is a [[Barcelona Metro]] station, located in the [[Mercabarna|Mercabarna market complex]] of the [[Zona Franca (Barcelona)|Zona Franca]] in the [[Sants-Montju\u00efc]] district of [[Barcelona]]. The station is served by [[Barcelona Metro line 9|line L9]].<ref name=planbcn>{{cite web | url = http://w20.bcn.cat/GuiaMap//default.aspx#x=26371&y=80231&z=5&c=K001&w=1380&h=830&base=GuiaMartorell | title = Pl\u00e0nolbcn | publisher = Ajuntament de Barcelona | language = Catalan | accessdate = 2015-02-03}}</ref><ref name=tmap>{{cite web | url = http://cartometro.com/cartes/metro-tram-barcelona/ | title = Track map of the Barcelona Metro | publisher = cartometro.com | accessdate = 2015-02-03}}</ref>\n\nThe station is located underneath the western approach to the Mercabarna market, with its only entrance provided by a staircase and elevator at the intersection of ''Carrer K'' and the ''Carrer Transversal 6,'' with a ticket office below ground. The two {{convert|108|m|adj=on}} long [[side platform]]s are at a lower level.<ref name=tmap/><ref name=trenscat>{{cite web | url = http://www.trenscat.com/tmb/09mercabarna_ct.html | title = Mercabarna | language = Catalan | publisher = trenscat.com | accessdate = 2016-09-18}}</ref>\n\nThe station was opened in 2016, at the time of the extension of line L9 from [[Zona Universit\u00e0ria (Barcelona Metro)|Zona Universitaria station]] to [[Airport T1 (Barcelona Metro)|Aeroport T1 station]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.trenscat.com/tmb/09mercabarna_ct.html Trenscat.com]\n\n{{Barcelona Metro line 9}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mercabarna (Barcelona Metro)}}\n[[Category:Barcelona Metro line 9 stations]]\n[[Category:Transport in Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2016]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox station\n| name            = Mercabarna\n| type            = [[Barcelona Metro]] [[rapid transit]] station\n| style           = \n| image           = File:Estaci\u00f3 de Mercabarna.jpg\n| image_caption   = \n| address         = Mercabarna, [[Barcelona]]\n| country         = \n| coordinates     = {{coord|41|20|01|N|2|01|42|E|region:ES-CT_type:landmark_source:kolossus-nlwiki|display=inline,title}}\n| line            = \n| other           = \n| structure       = Underground\n| platform        = \n| depth           = \n| levels          = \n| tracks          = \n| parking         = \n| bicycle         = \n| opened          = 2016\n| closed          = \n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = \n| ADA             = \n| code            = \n| owned           = [[Transports Metropolitans 